<DOC><DOCNO> AP890817-0185 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-89 0150EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-TelephoneImports     08-17 0238</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Telephone Imports,0245</SECOND><HEAD>Hearing Set on Dumping Charges</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. International Trade Commission says ithas set a final hearing Oct. 31 on the request of American telephonemanufacturers for steep anti-dumping duties on small business phonesystems from Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.   The action Wednesday follows a U.S. Commerce Departmentpreliminary finding that 12 manufacturers in the three Asiancountries were exporting the systems to the United States at pricesfar below fair market value.   The purpose of the hearing is to determine whether U.S. makersare substantially threatened by the imports. The commission isexpected to announce its decision in November.   A U.S. government investigation was requested by AmericanTelephone andamp; Telegraph Co. and Comdial Corp.   ATandamp;T and other U.S. makers said the Asian manufacturers hadcaptured about 60 percent of the U.S. market for small businessphone systems and their own sales had declined dramatically. Thesystems provide telephone links within companies separate from thegeneral telephone network, to which they may be connected foroutside calling.   Foreign companies named in the action included Toshiba andMatsushita of Japan, Samsung and Goldstar in South Korea and TaiwanNitsuko and Sun Moon Star in Taiwan. The Commerce Department saidthe United States in 1988 imported $775.7 million worth of smallbusiness phone systems and partly assembled systems from Japan, $342million worth from Taiwan and $227 million worth from South Korea.</TEXT></DOC>